omen’s consumer interests to the fore. Due to their exclusion from formal politics and paid employment, many Canadian women turned their consumer roles into personal and social opportunities. They sought solutions in the consumer sphere to isolation, upward mobility, personal expression, and family survival. They transformed consumer culture into an arena of political engagement. Yet if Canadian women viewed consumption as a tool of empowerment, so did they wield consumption as a tool of exclusion. As Purchasing Power reveals, Canadian women of privileged race and class status tended to disparage racialized and lower income women’s consumer habits. In so doing, they constructed notions of taste that defined who – and who did not – belong in the modern Canadian nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConsumer behaviorzCanadaxHistory. 0aConsumption (Economics)xPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistory. 0aConsumption (Economics)xSocial aspectszCanadaxHistory. 0aConsumption (Economics)zCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen consumerszCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen, WhitezCanadaxEconomic conditions. 0aWomen, WhitezCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  acitizenship.  aco-operative movements.  aconsumer culture.  aconsumer studies.  aconsumption.  agender.  ahistory.  ahome economics.  ashopping.  atemperance.  atwentieth-century Canadian history.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262586040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442625860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442625860.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles